sions during the Cold War, yet much of the intelligence history of these countries remains unknown. In The Bridge in the Parks, intelligence scholars from across the Five Eyes come together to present case studies detailing the varied successes and struggles their countries experienced in the world of Cold War counter-intelligence. The case studies in The Bridge in the Parks draw on newly declassified documents across a variety of topics, including civil liberties, agent handling, wiretapping, and international relations. Collectively, these studies highlight how Cold War intelligence history is more nuanced than it has often been portrayed – and much like in the world of intelligence, nothing is ever entirely as it seems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCold War. 0aIntelligence servicexHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aCanadian history.  aCold War.  aCommonwealth security.  aFive Eyes.  aGouzenko.  aIntelligence.  aMI5.  aRCMP.  acounter-intelligence.  aespionage.  ainternational relations.  asecret agents.  asecurity agencies.  atradecraft.  awiretapping.1 aBencivenni, Marcella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreen, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeery, Phillip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHewitt, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKealey, Gregory S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLomas, Daniel W. B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolinaro, Dennis G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolinaro, Dennis G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ed